As a follow up to this, if anyone has any contacts at Google that you 
think might be able to help me out getting around their rate limiting 
for my image evolution experiments please let me know.  I think that is 
currently the main impediment to taking this work further.

Thanks!
Josh



On 07/26/2012 11:22 AM, Joshua Auerbach wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Hi all,
&gt;
&gt; Figured I would spread the word about some of my recent publications 
&gt; employing CPPN-NEAT for any of you that may be interested, but were 
&gt; unable to attend my presentations at GECCO and ALife.
&gt;
&gt; The first two are on evolving CPPN encoded (simulated) robot 
&gt; morphologies to explore different relationships between environmental 
&gt; complexity and the complexity of evolved robots.  Unlike our previous 
&gt; work in this area here robots are created out of rigid body triangular 
&gt; mesh components.
&gt;
&gt; Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.  On the Relationship Between 
&gt; Environmental and Morphological Complexity in Evolved Robots. 2012 
&gt; Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference (GECCO 2012). 
&gt; Philadelphia, PA, July, 2012.
&gt;
&gt; Paper available here: 
&gt; http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_gecco_2012.pdf
&gt; Accompanying videos available here: http://tinyurl.com/GECCO2012-Videos
&gt;
&gt; Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.  On the Relationship Between 
&gt; Environmental and Mechanical Complexity in Evolved Robots. 13th 
&gt; International Conference on the Synthesis and Simulation of Living 
&gt; Systems (ALife XIII).  East Lansing, MI, July, 2012.
&gt;
&gt; Paper: 
&gt; http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_alife_2012.pdf
&gt; Accompanying videos: http://tinyurl.com/ALife13-Videos
&gt;
&gt; The third paper (really just an extended abstract) presents the idea 
&gt; and some initial experiments on employing Google Search By Image in 
&gt; lieu of interactive evolution (as is done in Picbreeder) to evolve 
&gt; images that are interesting to people.  The idea is that Google&#39;s 
&gt; image database should indirectly capture what people find interesting 
&gt; and so perhaps crafting fitness functions informed by search results 
&gt; from this service could evolve interesting images without direct human 
&gt; involvement.  My presentation on this paper was awarded Best 
&gt; Presentation in The Humanities and ALife track.
&gt;
&gt; Joshua E. Auerbach.  Automated Evolution of Interesting Images.  13th 
&gt; International Conference on the Synthesis and Simulation of Living 
&gt; Systems (ALife XIII).  East Lansing, MI, July, 2012.
&gt;
&gt; Paper: 
&gt; http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_alife_2012b.pdf
&gt;
&gt; Feel free to contact me with any questions, feedback or additional input.
&gt;
&gt; Thanks!
&gt; -Josh
