            &lt;p&gt; Hi all,&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Figured I would spread the word about some of my recent
              publications employing CPPN-NEAT for any of you that may
              be interested, but were unable to attend my presentations
              at GECCO and ALife.&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              The first two are on evolving CPPN encoded (simulated)
              robot morphologies to explore different relationships
              between environmental complexity and the complexity of
              evolved robots.&nbsp; Unlike our previous work in this area
              here robots are created out of rigid body triangular mesh
              components.&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.&nbsp; On the
              Relationship Between Environmental and Morphological
              Complexity in Evolved Robots. 2012 Genetic and
              Evolutionary Computation Conference (GECCO 2012).&nbsp;
              Philadelphia, PA, July, 2012. &lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Paper available here:
              &lt;a moz-do-not-send=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;moz-txt-link-freetext&quot;
href=&quot;http://www.cs.uvm.edu/%7Ejauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_gecco_2012.pdf&quot;&gt;http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_gecco_2012.pdf&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
              Accompanying videos available here: &lt;a
                moz-do-not-send=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;moz-txt-link-freetext&quot;
                href=&quot;http://tinyurl.com/GECCO2012-Videos&quot;&gt;http://tinyurl.com/GECCO2012-Videos&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.&nbsp; On the
              Relationship Between Environmental and Mechanical
              Complexity in Evolved Robots. 13th International
              Conference on the Synthesis and Simulation of Living
              Systems (ALife XIII).&nbsp; East Lansing, MI, July, 2012. &lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              Paper:
              &lt;a moz-do-not-send=&quot;true&quot; class=&quot;moz-txt-link-freetext&quot;
href=&quot;http://www.cs.uvm.edu/%7Ejauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_alife_2012.pdf&quot;&gt;http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_alife_2012.pdf&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
              Accompanying videos: &lt;a moz-do-not-send=&quot;true&quot;
                class=&quot;moz-txt-link-freetext&quot;
                href=&quot;http://tinyurl.com/ALife13-Videos&quot;&gt;http://tinyurl.com/ALife13-Videos&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;
              &lt;br&gt;
              The third paper (really just an extended abstract)
              presents the idea and some initial experiments on
              employing Google Search By Image in lieu of interactive
              evolution (as is done in Picbreeder) to evolve images that
              are interesting to people.&nbsp; The idea is that Google&#39;s
              image database should indirectly capture what people find
              interesting and so perhaps crafting fitness functions
              informed by search results from this service could evolve
              interesting images without direct human involvement.&nbsp; My
              presentation on this paper was awarded Best Presentation
              in The Humanities and ALife track.&lt;br&gt;
            &lt;/p&gt;
